%text Two questions need to be answered. Is $F(x,y)$ homogenous? And if yes, then what is it's degree?
% \begin{align}
\text{If }F(x,y) &= \fx \\ \text{ then } F \left(\lambda x, \lambda y \right) &= \lfx \\ &= \dfrac{\lambda\cdot \left(\sqrt{x^2 + y^2} + y\right)}{\lambda x} \\ &= \underbrace{\lambda^0}_{=1}\cdot \left[\fx \right] \\ &= \lambda^0 \cdot F(x,y) \end{align} %text Hence, the fact that $F(\lambda x, \lambda y) = \lambda^n\cdot F(x,y)$ proves that $F(x,y)$ is a homogenous function And the fact that $n = 0$ tells us that it is a homogenous function of degree $0$%
